<div id="review_1299893380" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1299893380" />
    <a title="Lela" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9920233-lela"><img alt="Lela" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1434757168p2/9920233.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1299893380?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lela" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lela" href="/user/show/9920233-lela">Lela</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/20002857-the-blind-owl">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1299893380" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7332401828444219705">I think I&apos;m going to leave this unrated. I can&apos;t say I liked it, but, eventually I had to keep reading to see how it could possibly conclude - and it didn&apos;t conclude, really. It just stopped. A surreal tale of obsession, madness, opium induced perceptions, the strangeness of old relationships, dancing, poisoned wine, cobras, abandonment, old age, futility, love, hate and many, many other ideas and things. There are a few ideas about this book that arise from its being banned in Iran. One being i</span>
  <span id="freeText7332401828444219705" style="display:none">I think I'm going to leave this unrated. I can't say I liked it, but, eventually I had to keep reading to see how it could possibly conclude - and it didn't conclude, really. It just stopped. A surreal tale of obsession, madness, opium induced perceptions, the strangeness of old relationships, dancing, poisoned wine, cobras, abandonment, old age, futility, love, hate and many, many other ideas and things. There are a few ideas about this book that arise from its being banned in Iran. One being it is a metaphor for living under the Shah. Possible? Certainly. Certain? Of course not. Another explanation is it lead to too many suicides so had to be banned. That one is even harder to believe. Enough of that. I am glad I read the book though there were a few phrases repeated endlessly which I grew very tired of - "stub end of a cucumber" being one of them - there are many, many other scream-inducing repetitions! So back to my original statement: I am not going to rate because I just can't.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7332401828444219705" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


