  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_570587181" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/570587181" />
    <a title="Orsolya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5647191-orsolya"><img alt="Orsolya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1603139114p2/5647191.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/570587181?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Orsolya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Orsolya" href="/user/show/5647191-orsolya">Orsolya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780802131805" href="/book/show/45967.The_Blind_Owl">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5647191-orsolya?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5647191-orsolya?shelf=library-2">library-2</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5647191-orsolya?shelf=other">other</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5647191-orsolya?shelf=folk-tales-short-stories">folk-tales-short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer570587181" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2426049583960905552">Due to my obsession with owls and having previously dated a Persian man; I am familiar with the connotation of owls in Iranian culture. Hearing that Sadegh Hedayat, the author of “The Blind Owl”, lived in Iran and then committed suicide at age 48, was enough to draw me in. <br/><br/>“The Blind Owl” has a magnetic draw starting with the first word. Following a stream of consciousness style (don’t expect dialogue, character names, etc); Hedayat pulls the reader in full-force with heavy literary, symbolical,</span>
  <span id="freeText2426049583960905552" style="display:none">Due to my obsession with owls and having previously dated a Persian man; I am familiar with the connotation of owls in Iranian culture. Hearing that Sadegh Hedayat, the author of “The Blind Owl”, lived in Iran and then committed suicide at age 48, was enough to draw me in. <br /><br />“The Blind Owl” has a magnetic draw starting with the first word. Following a stream of consciousness style (don’t expect dialogue, character names, etc); Hedayat pulls the reader in full-force with heavy literary, symbolical, and metaphorical means. This is clearly not a book for everyone; but for those readers who enjoy depth, “The Blind Owl” is a satisfying novel. <br /><br />Oftentimes, one cannot distinguish if the narrator is drugged, in a fantasy, reality, dreaming, etc; but it doesn’t matter. The actual events described are of less importance than that of the philosophical and psychological messaged conveyed. In fact, Hedayat smoothly and seamlessly digs at dark inner thoughts readers may have experienced in secret and “The Blind Owl” thus feels like reading the author’s diary (or even the reader’s own); versus a fictional narrator’s story. Although dark, the novel is a beautiful and relatable in its desolation. Even the language translation holds no bounds and doesn’t create any loss.<br /><br />“The Blind Owl” is very “readable” with a steady pace, despite it not conforming to a traditional novelistic style. Furthermore, some reviewers complain of repetitive phrases which is not an author error in this case, but the opium and maniac-oppressive/obsessive thoughts (plus symbolism) of the narrator. Again, “The Blind Owl” is not for everyone as apparently it is too heavy for some readers. <br /><br />Speaking of ‘heavy’, Hedayat doesn’t implore regular chapter breaks which along with the text, can be too much to “take in” all at once despite how wonderful the novel is. Reading breaks are encouraged for full enjoyment.<br /><br />The ebb and flow of the narrator’s consciousness and stupor mimics the reality of life and mystic thoughts and continues to release believability. In fact, some of the quotes are so clear, that they directly flow as the reader’s own thoughts. <br /><br />“The Blind Owl” briefly visits religious topics, albeit in an unexpected way of that of traditional Islamic-induced cultural studies. This is refreshing and strengthens the originality of the novel. Clearly, the novel also discusses death. Hedayat’s narrator visits this so rationally, that one forgets that it may possibly be irrational to have these thoughts in the first place. Basically, “The Blind Owl” lingers on dark thoughts with morbid appeal and yet weaves them with beauty and understanding. <br /><br />The conclusion of “The Blind Owl” is somewhat abrupt and doesn’t necessarily tie all the loose strings. However, it makes sense, feels natural, and fits spotlessly within the narrator’s characterization. <br /><br />“The Blind Owl” is an extraordinary literary stream of consciousness work. Passionate, multi-leveled, and philosophical; it <u>has</u> to be more of an autobiographical diary than a fictional novel. It if it is pure fiction, than it is a masterpiece and the author is a genius. “The Blind Owl” is highly recommended for intelligent readers. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2426049583960905552" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


