<div id="review_3144190690" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3144190690" />
    <a title="Joseph Schreiber" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12466654-joseph-schreiber"><img alt="Joseph Schreiber" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509577436p2/12466654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3144190690?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joseph Schreiber" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joseph Schreiber" href="/user/show/12466654-joseph-schreiber">Joseph Schreiber</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3144190690" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16660160677181906751">I wanted to rate this between 3 and 4 stars. Typically my ratings rise with time and if I write about the book and I feel it will inch toward 4. So be it. Reading this tale of madness is an experience, I was often reminded of The Cabinet of Dr Caligari, but with an opium drenched Persian setting. But that is a horror film, one that ends in an asylum, the horror here is much more intensely real and surreal. This book triggered suicides, and the author himself took his own life. Thus it sits much </span>
  <span id="freeText16660160677181906751" style="display:none">I wanted to rate this between 3 and 4 stars. Typically my ratings rise with time and if I write about the book and I feel it will inch toward 4. So be it. Reading this tale of madness is an experience, I was often reminded of The Cabinet of Dr Caligari, but with an opium drenched Persian setting. But that is a horror film, one that ends in an asylum, the horror here is much more intensely real and surreal. This book triggered suicides, and the author himself took his own life. Thus it sits much more heavily in the stomach. Nonetheless, a vital read.<br />I read the Noori translation which has a very interesting discussion of translation and the tendency to consider "smoothness" the hallmark of success. This version, by a bilingual Persian-English speaker uses the original manuscript and makes no effort to spoon feed the reader, enhancing the discomfort of being inside the poor narrator's addled brain.<br />An expanded review can be found here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://roughghosts.com/2020/01/25/delirium-desire-and-despair-the-blind-owl-by-sadegh-hedayat/">https://roughghosts.com/2020/01/25/de...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="16660160677181906751" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
